 a Priest Forever”: An Anti-Heretical Mnemonic Icon -- tDecoding Medieval Enigmas -- t14 The Tsar’s Hidden Wisdom -- t15 Enigmatic Motifs in Medieval Russian Icons -- t16 The Sacralization of Canon Law in Rus (Thirteenth–Sixteenth Centuries) -- t17 The Sovereign’s Two Names (Potapii Maksimovich the Grandson of Matvei, or Vasilii Ivanovich Shuiskii) -- tPlates -- tAbstracts and Keywords -- tIndex of Art works and Manuscripts -- tIndex of Persons and Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEnigma in Rus and Medieval Slavic Cultures is a thematic essay volume to investigate the history and function of enigma in Orthodox Slavic cultures with a special focus on the cultural history of Rus and Muscovy. Its seventeen case studies across disciplinary boundaries analyze Slavic biblical and patristic translations, liturgical commentaries, occult divinatory texts, and dream interpretations. Slavic riddles inscribed on walls and compilations of riddles in question-and-answer format are all subjects of this volume. Not only written, but also pictorial enigmas are examined, together with their relationships to texts suggesting novel methodologies for their deciphering. This kaleidoscopic survey of Enigma in Rus and Medieval Slavic Cultures by an international group of scholars demonstrates the historiographical challenges that medieval enigmatic thought poses for researchers and offers new approaches to the interpretation of medieval sources, both verbal and visual.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Alexander von Humboldt Stiftung  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aGroßfürstentum Moskau. 4aMittelalter. 4aSemiotik. 4aSlavische Sprachen. 4arussische Kunst. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aSemiotics, middle ages, Musc